rocesses -- tIntroduction -- t12 Mediterranean, Near East, and Iran -- t12.A Economic Dynamics in the Hellenistic Empires -- t12.B Economic Dynamics in the Arsakid Empire -- t12.C Institutions and Economic Relations in the Roman Empire: Consumption, Supply, and Coordination -- t13 Economic Development under the Greek Kingdoms of Central Asia to the Kushan Empire: Empire, Migration, and Monasteries -- t14 Political, Corporate, and Ritual Economic Processes of Early Historic South Asia -- t15 Structures and Dynamics of the Early Imperial Chinese Economy -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe second volume of the Handbook describes different extractive economies in the world regions that have been outlined in the first volume. A wide range of economic actors - from kings and armies to cities and producers - are discussed within different imperial settings as well as the tools, which enabled and constrained economic outcomes. A central focus are nodes of consumption that are visible in the archaeological and textual records of royal capitals, cities, religious centers, and armies that were stationed, in some cases permanently, in imperial frontier zones. Complementary to the multipolar concentrations of consumption are the fiscal-tributary structures of the empires vis-à-vis other institutions that had the capacity to extract, mobilize, and concentrate resources and wealth. Larger volumes of state-issued coinage in various metals show the new role of coinage in taxation, local economic activities, and social practices, even where textual evidence is absent. Given the overwhelming importance of agriculture, the volume also analyses forms of agrarian development, especially around cities and in imperial frontier zones. Special consideration is given to road- and water-management systems for which there is now sufficient archaeological and documentary evidence to enable cross-disciplinary comparative research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEconomic historyyTo 500. 0aMineral industriesxHistory.1 aDwivedi, Mamta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFabian, Lara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFabian, Lara.1 aHoo, Milinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeese-Messing, Kathrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorris, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReden, Sitta von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReden, Sitta, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTaasob, Razieh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeaverdyck, Eli J. S.1 aWeaverdyck, Eli J. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1z978311076682008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG0 cEPUBz97831106049310 cprintz978311060452840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110607642zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110607642zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110607642/original  a978-3-11-075400-1 EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075408-7 EBOOK PACKAGE Hi